                            <p>Learning how to help your children with anxiety starts with recognising the symptoms. The symptoms can look different for each type of anxiety disorder. However, the following are some common signs of anxiety in children:</p>
                            <p>&nbsp;</p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Worrying about or are fearful of everyday situations</li>
                                <li>Being confused and unable to concentrate.</li>
                                <li>Avoiding new and difficult situations.</li>
                                <li>Being socially isolated or extremely shy.</li>
                                <li>Staying always on edge or nervous.</li>
                                <li>Constantly tired and unable to sleep.</li>
                            </ul>
                            <p>&nbsp;</p>
                            <p>Physical symptoms that may accompany anxiety include:</p>
                            <p>&nbsp;</p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Rapid heartbeat and sweating</li>
                                <li>Shallow breathing and shortness of breath</li>
                                <li>Restlessness and shaking</li>
                                <li>Dry mouth, stomach pains, nausea, digestion issues</li>
                                <li></li>
                            </ul>
                            <p>&nbsp;</p>
                            <p>If these experiences are interfering with their daily functioning, responsibilities and quality of life, your child may have an anxiety disorder.&nbsp; Find more about different types of anxiety disorders in the next block.</p>
                        </div>
