                            <p><strong>The six most common anxiety disorders that can affect your child are: </strong></p>
                            <p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>
                            <ol>
                                <li><strong>Generalised anxiety disorder</strong>: A severe ongoing anxiety which could be about a number of things, such as work, money, relationships.</li>
                                <li><strong>Social phobia</strong>: A marked and persistent fear of being embarrassed in social situations</li>
                                <li><strong>Specific phobia</strong>: An intense and irrational fear of a specific situation or object</li>
                                <li><strong>Panic disorders</strong>: The presence of repeated, unexpected panic attacks and worry about having another panic attack.</li>
                                <li><strong>Obsessive compulsive disorder</strong>: Experiencing repeated obsessions (unwanted thoughts and impulses) and/or compulsions (urge to act a certain way or complete a task) that creates distress or impairment.</li>
                                <li><strong>Post traumatic stress disorder</strong>: Experiencing certain symptoms following a traumatic event</li>
                            </ol>
                        </div>
